article.description: Yolanda Griffith had 18 points and seven rebounds Sunday night, helping the Sacramento Monarchs end their season on a roll with a 72-63 victory over the Minnesota Lynx.
article.headline: Monarchs face top-seeded L.A. in playoffs
article.linkText: Monarchs cap regular season on a roll
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- The Sacramento Monarchs had something
to prove in their regular-season finale.

"You want to go into the playoffs on a high note," forward
DeMya Walker said. "After we lost this week to L.A., we wanted to
win out and we were able to do it."

Yolanda Griffith had 18 points and seven rebounds Sunday night,
helping the Monarchs end their season on a three-game winning
streak with a 72-63 victory over the Minnesota Lynx.

The Monarchs finished 18-16 but still had to settle for the
fourth seed in the Western Conference playoffs. They'll start their
best-of-three series with top-seeded Los Angeles on Friday in
Sacramento.

"It's L.A., we'll be ready," said Griffith, who also had five
steals and two blocks.

Minnesota, also 18-16, took the third seed because of a
tiebreaker and will host second-seeded Seattle on Saturday. The
Lynx had a better record than the Monarchs against teams finishing
.500 or better.

Kara Lawson scored 17 points and had a career-high eight assists
for the Monarchs, who used an 11-3 run in the fourth quarter to
break a 49-all tie and take the lead for good.

Svetlana Abrosimova made four 3-pointers and led the Lynx with
21 points. Nicole Ohlde added 15 points and seven rebounds.

The Monarchs played without point guard Ticha Penicheiro, who
sprained her foot in Saturday's playoff-clinching victory over
Houston. She's expected to return for the series against the
Sparks.

The Minnesota Timberwolves' Kevin Garnett and Sacramento Kings
guard Bobby Jackson took in the game from courtside seats.
